-----level 00-----
# Goal : password stored in readme

# Commands Used : 
ls 
cat readme

# What I learned : 'cat' prints the contents of the file where as 'ls' shows teh directories and file present.


-----level 01-----
# Goal : Find password from the file named -

# Commands Used : 
ls -a 
cat ./-

# What I learned : Filename with SPECIAL character needs SPECIAL treatment


-----level 02-----
# Goal : The filename has --spaces in the filename--

# Commands Used : 
ls -a 
cat ./"--spaces int he fiename--"

# What I learned : file with spaces in the filename needs "<filename>"


-----level 03-----
# Goal : finding hidden files 

# Commands Used : 
ls -a
cd inhere
cat "...Hiding-From-You"

# What I learned : using ls -a we can find hidden files and directories



-----level 04-----
# Goal : password in a human-readable file in inhere directory

# Commands Used : 
ls 
cd inhere
ls -la
file ./-file*
cat ./-file07

# What I learned :using the file command to identify the filetype, using the * evaluate all the files with filenamme starting from '-file'


-----level 05-----
# Goal : the file has properties :
         human-readable 
         1033 bytes in size
         not executable

# Commands Used : 
ls 
find . -size 1033c
cd maybehere
cat ./.file2

# What I learned :using find / don't forget to use 'man'


-----level 06-----
# Goal : file is saved somewhere on the server and has properties 
          owned by user bandit7
          owned by group bandit6
          33 bytes in size

# Commands Used : 
find . -user bandit7 -group bandit6 -size 33c 2>/dev/null

# What I learned : you can group conditions in find command / use '2>/dev/null' to send useless output to void 


-----level 07-----
# Goal : password is stored in data.txt next to the word millionth

# Commands Used : 
ls 
file data.txt
grep "millionth" data.txt

# What I learned : use grep with the word you want to search 


-----level 08-----
# Goal : password in data.txt and occurs only once in the file 

# Commands Used : 
ls 
sort data.txt | uniq -u 

# What I learned : use of piping to make the output from first command the input of second command


-----level 09-----
# Goal : password in data.txt in one of the few human-readable strings preceded by several "="

# Commands Used : 
ls 
strings data.txt

# What I learned : using "strings" help extarct all the human readable text


-----level 10-----
# Goal : base64 encoded data

# Commands Used : 
ls 
cat data.txt | base64 -d

# What I learned : base64 is encoded language 


-----level 11-----
# Goal : lowercase and uppercase letters have been rotated by 13 positions

# Commands Used : 
ls 
cat data.txt | tr "ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz" "NOPQRSTUVWXYZABCDEFGHIJKLMnopqrstuvwxyzabcdefghijklm"

# What I learned : using tr to translate 


-----level 12-----
# Goal : hexdump password

# Common Used :
xxd -r
gunzip
bunzip2
tar -xf

# What I learned : hexdump is a command line utlity that displays the contents in human readable format.


-----level 13-----
# Goal : no password but the ssh key

# Common Used :
cat sshkey.private
exit
ssh -i password.txt bandit14@bandit.labs.overthewire.org -p 2220

# What I learned : use ssh on the local machine by using -i along with the filename (it directly log into the bandit 14)


-----level 14-----
# Goal : password by submitting the current level password to port 30000 on localhost

# Common Used :
cat /etc/bandit_pass/bandit14
nc localhost 30000          ---> it asks for password type and enter

# What I learned : command nc (netcat) connects to the localhost


-----level 15-----
# Goal : password by submitting the current password to the localhost at port 30001 using SSL/TLS encryption

# Common Used :
openssl s_client connect localhost:30001

# What I learned : 'openssl' is the command/toolkit that helps SSL/TLS encryption. Using SSL/TLS the data is not readable / encrypted 


